Dr. Georges Bwelle Brings Free Medical Aid to Remote Villages in Cameroon
Bwelle and his team spend almost every weekend treating hundreds of patients
There are not many doctors in the West African country, only one for 5,000 people
Vote here or with your mobile device
Dr. Georges Bwelle is one of the top 10 of the "CNN Heroes of 2013".
You can vote for him or one of the other heroes in the top 10 to choose the "CNN Hero of the Year".
The winner receives 250,000 dollars to continue his extraordinary work.
For 21 years, Georges Bwelle saw his sick father repeatedly losing consciousness and traveling to hospitals that did not have the means to help him.
Jamef Bwelle was injured in a car accident near Yaoundé, the capital of Cameroon, in 1981.
At first he had only one broken arm, but then an inflammation formed, which spread to his brain and caused a hematoma there, which was to affect him for the rest of his life.
"There were no neurosurgeons in Cameroon," says Georges Bwelle.
We would have brought him out of Cameroon if we had had the money.
Instead, Bwelle spent years accompanying his father in overcrowded clinics and hospitals to get the treatment they had to offer.
"It's not easy," comments Bwelle.
You can leave the house at five in the morning and run to the hospital to be the first, and yet it is not first.
There are many patients.
Some people die even because they have to wait.
The situation has hardly changed since Bwelle's father died in 2002.
In Cameroon, there is only one doctor for 5,000 people each, according to the World Health Organisation.
In contrast, the ratio in the United States is with a doctor for 413 people.
But even if there were a doctor for her, most Cameroonians would not be able to afford the visit.
Two out of five people in the country live below the poverty line and nearly three-quarters of health spending in the country is private.
"The only problem they have is poverty," says Bwelle.
And poverty makes it impossible to enjoy life.
His father and so many of his fellow countrymen suffered allowed to see in Bwelle the decision to do something about it.
Dr. Georges Bwelle and his volunteer team have carried out 700 free operations last year.
He became a doctor himself and works as a vascular surgeon at the Central Hospital in Yaoundé.
He also founded a non-profit organization called ASCOVIME, which travels to rural areas on weekends and offers free medical care.
Since 2008, he and his volunteer group have helped nearly 32,000 people.
Almost every Friday, he and up to 30 people squeeze in minibuses and travel with the tied medical equipment on the roof over unpaved terrain to the villages that need help.
It is not always everything that goes smoothly.
More than once, they had to push the vehicles through rivers and mud.
But when they arrive, they will be welcomed like heroes: a feast, song and dancing and the best accommodation the place has to offer.
In these villages, free medical care is really a cause for celebrating and barrel – with its broad smile and its limitless energy – likes to be present at the cheerful celebration.
The next morning, the team then begins examining hundreds of patients.
"We treat 500 people per trip," says Bwelle.
They come from a radius of 60 kilometres around the village – and that on foot.
Each of these weekend clinics offers medical care in a range of areas.
Many people are treated with malaria, tuberculosis, malnutrition, diabetes, parasites and sexually transmitted diseases.
Others receive crutches, donated glasses or free birth certificates – a document required for school, but many poor families simply cannot afford.
In the evening, the team performs simple operations with local anaesthetic.
The operations usually take place in a school, town hall or apartment; after the procedure, the patients get up and go to the recreation area to make room for the next.
The lighting for the surgery and the disinfection equipment is fed by the group's generator and so bshaft and its volunteers work until the early hours of the morning on Sunday.
It is a tiring workload, but the village musicians usually help to keep the team motivated.
"They drum the whole night so that we can stay awake and continue our work," says Bwelle.
On Sunday, the team then drives back to the city, tired, but proud of the work done.
The group – a mixture of Cameroonian doctors and foreign medical students – has performed 700 free operations last year and knows that with her work it makes a huge difference for the people it helps.
One man explained that the free operation of a hernia he had received now enabled him to work again.
"That changes the future of my family," said the man.
In addition to the weekend clinics and his work as a surgeon in the hospital, Bwelle also works at night in private clinics in Yaoundé.
With this second job he finances 60% of his non-profit activity, according to Bwelle; the rest comes from private donations.
"I really don't know when he sleeps," says Katie O'Malley, who is studying medicine at Drexel University in Philadelphia for the second year and volunteers in Bwelle's group.
He is always either in the hospital or tries to raise money for the organization so that he can go to these campaigns.
For medical and nursing students such as O'Malley, who come from the USA and Europe and support Bwelle, this is an opportunity to gain practical experience that they would never get at home.
“We can be involved in surgeries where we help to dab blood or the instruments for Dr. Hold Bwelle," explains O'Malley.
This would never be possible in America as a medical student in the second year.
The students usually pay for their journey to Cameroon themselves and bring frequently donated medical materials.
But once they are in Yaoundé, Bwelle takes over the accommodation, transport and instructions.
"He is without a doubt a hero," says O'Malley.
He dedicates his life to this organization and his desire to help the Cameroonian people knows no bounds.
For Bwelle, the almost constant work is not a burden.
To help others to live a happier life and thus fulfill a promise that he has made to his father gives him great joy.
"I'm so happy when I do this work," says Bwelle.
And I think of my father.
I hope he sees what I am doing.
I do it to make people laugh again and to relieve the pain.
