Scientists could shed more light on the connection between a dog's tail flucration and its mood.
Previous research had shown that happy dogs with the tail were more tocline to the right (from the dog's point of view), while in nervous dogs it was the left side.
But now scientists are saying that other dogs can perceive and react to these subtle differences.
Professor Georgio Vallortigara, a neuroscientist at the University of Trento, said: "It is well known in humans that the left and right brains react differently to stimuli that evoke positive or negative emotions."
Here we have tried to see this in other species.
He also noticed that in dogs, just as in humans, the right brain hemisphere was responsible for the movement of the left side and vice versa, and that the two hemispheres played different roles in the feelings.
To learn more about how dogs react to the lateral tail flucoping, the researchers monitored the animals while these films were looking at by other dogs.
They measured the heart rate of the four-legged friends and analysed the behaviour.
Probably we will soon understand why the cock moves in one direction, sometimes in the other
Professor Vallortigara said: "We have shown the dogs films with dogs – either a lifelike version or a silhouette to eliminate distracting other aspects, and we were able to control the movement of the tail more to the left or right."
When the animals saw how an otherwise expressionless dog moved the tail to the right (as seen from the perspective of the winging dog), they remained completely relaxed.
But if the tail tilt was mainly to the left (again from the perspective of the dog that waves), so their heart rate rose and they looked restless.
According to Professor Vallortigara, the dogs do not communicate with each other deliberately through these movements.
Rather, he is convinced that the dogs have learned from experience what movements they should worry about and when not.
He said: "When you have different encounters with other dogs and the waging with the cock is more associated with friendly behavior in one direction and the right side produces less friendly behavior, then you react on the basis of these experiences."
The researchers say that the findings could help dog owners, veterinarians and trainers to better understand the emotions of their animal.
John Bradshaw, an expert on dog behaviour and guest holder at the Faculty of Veterinary Medicine at the University of Bristol, said that this was not the first study to investigate whether left and right was important for dogs.
