What happens to my email?
E-Mail is actually called an electronic letter.
Was the correspondence secret technically implemented in the design of the Internet service e-mail, similar to traditional mail?
The design of early Internet services focused on making communication possible.
Therefore, the basic technical protocols were not taken to create a stable foundation for an listen-safe correspondence.
Therefore, a conventional email is more like an open postcard than a sealed letter.
If the user sends "Anna" to "Benni" a mail, are then the computers of the two connected directly?
The e-mail program or Anna's browser sends the mail to the mail server of its service provider in the first step.
For example, if it has a GMail account, it would be Google.
This mail server sends the content to the provider that Benni uses.
On the route, the mail can be run via several other servers on the Internet.
Bennie can then call the content to his provider.
Are conventional e-mails read on their way through the net?
Most mails are read several times on the go by software robots.
The sender's provider usually checks whether the mail carries a malicious program as an attachment.
A virus check is also made on the recipient systems.
In addition, the providers check whether it is an annoying and unwanted spam email that is immediately deleted or at least sorted away into a spam folder.
Do the robots have another task?
For systems such as GMail, the robot also determines the information Google needs to base context advertising.
If Anna and Benni communicate via GMail via their upcoming holiday trip, Google can display appropriate links to holiday offers.
Do unknown people also keeping the emails?
The probability that unauthorized persons will read an email is extremely low.
In theory, however, this is possible.
In companies, administrators often have the opportunity to read electronic mail.
Law enforcement agencies and intelligence agencies also have legal opportunities to intercept or take note of e-mails.
In addition, there are possible illegal spying actions.
Is it possible to protect e-mails against reading?
With encryption according to the OpenPGP standard, an e-mail can be effectively encrypted against reading.
With great technical effort, it is also possible to disguise the metadata of an e-mail communication, so that it is not even easily possible to recognise who has communicated with whom.
How important are Yahoo and Google in the email market in Germany?
According to an investigation by Convio Consulting from August 2013, Yahoo and Google play only a minor role in the mainly privately used mailboxes.
While the shares of Yahoo-Mail were last, GMail from Google was able to gain significant growth.
