FAA: Passengers can now use electronic devices in aircraft (but no phone calls)
From takeoff to landing, travellers can now use their electronic devices to read, work, play, play music and watch films, but cannot make calls with their mobile phones, according to the new guidelines issued on Thursday by the Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) in the USA.
However, passengers should not expect these changes to be implemented immediately.
FAA employee Michael Huerta explained at a press conference how quickly they would be implemented by the respective airline.
Airlines must demonstrate to the FAA that aircraft comply with the new directives and that they have updated the training manuals of the flight crew and the rules for storing the equipment in accordance with the new regulations.
The FAA said it had already received plans from a number of airlines that want to expand the use of portable electronic devices in aircraft.
Among these airlines were Delta and JetBlue.
"Depending on the condition of the plan, we could approve the advanced use of electronic devices very soon," the FAA announced in a statement.
Currently, passengers need to switch off smartphones, tablets and other devices when the aircraft doors are closed.
They can only take them off again when the aircraft has reached an altitude of three kilometres and the captain gives the green light.
Upon entry on the landing flight, passengers must switch them off again and they are not allowed to take off again before the aircraft has landed.
Under the new guidelines, airlines whose aircraft are protected against electronic interference could allow their passengers to use the devices even on take-off, landing and on the tarmac, the FAA explained.
Most new commercial aircraft and other aircraft converted to the use of Wi-Fi at higher heights should meet the criteria.
Laura Glading, president of the professional association of professional flight attendants, welcomed the changes.
"If the new regulation has been implemented safely – and we are working closely with the airline in this regard – will benefit both sides," Glading commented.
We are honestly tired of having to feel like watchdogs on this issue.
Nevertheless, Internet connections to surf, exchange emails, text messages or download data under three kilometres remain prohibited, the authority explained.
Passengers are encouraged to put smartphones, tablets and other devices into airplane mode.
So still no "Words With Friends", the Scrabble-like online game played by actor Alec Baldwin on his smartphone in 2011, when he had to publicly leave an American Airlines jet because he refused to shut down the device while the plane was parked at the gate.
And more heavy devices such as laptops must continue to be stowed, as there is a risk of injury if they fly through the cabin.
Mobile phone calls during the flight will also remain prohibited.
The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) does not have the regulatory competence for telephone calls, not the FAA.
FAA may suspend ban on certain electronic devices when take-off and landing
Last month, Mark Rosenker from the National Transportation Safety Board, security expert for national traffic issues on CBS News, said mobile phones are still considered a risk.
"Mobile phones are really a problem, not only because they could potentially cause interference with navigation devices, but because we know from the FCC that transmission from the air can also disturb transmitter masts," says Rosenker.
An industry advisory committee, launched by the FAA to investigate this issue, recommended last month that the government would allow a broader use of personal electronic devices.
In recent years, the pressure on the FAA has increased to loosen restrictions for use.
Critics such as Democratic Senator Claire McCaskill of Missouri believe that there are no valid security grounds for the ban.
The limitations are also increasingly difficult to enforce because the use of the devices has become ubiquitous.
In some studies, this is mentioned, which up to a third of passengers forget or ignores the switching off of the device.
The FAA began in 1966 to restrict the use of electronic devices by air travellers after reports of interference from navigation and communication devices by passengers were known, which were the latest technology trend at the time.
New aircraft are far more dependent on electrical systems than previous generations of aircraft, but they are also designed and approved by the FAA that they don't mind electronic interference.
Airlines have been offering passengers Wi-Fi for several years when the altitude is reached.
The fliers adapted to Wi-Fi systems are also less sensitive to interference.
The vast majority of passenger aircraft should be suitable for the greater use of electronic devices according to the new guidelines, said Huerta.
Today's electronic devices generally release considerably less radioblasting than previous generations.
E-readers, for example, only release minimal radiation when leafing through.
However, when downloading or sending data, the transmission values are stronger.
Amazon.com is one of the advocates of relaxing the restrictions on device usage by passengers.
In 2011, company employees invited a passenger plane full of Kindle e-reader and made a test flight to determine problems, but could not determine any.
Members of the FAA Advisory Committee expressed mixed feelings regarding the risk of using equipment.
Douglas Kidd from the National Association of Airline Passengers said he believes that the disturbance by the devices was real, even if the risk is minimal.
Other committee members said there are only individual reports of pilots who want to disturb aircraft system by the devices, and most of them are very old.
