New anti-nicotine vaccine could kill pleasure in smoking
Scientists have developed an anti-nicotine vaccine that could spoil the fun of smoking.
A single dose of the vaccine could protect mice from nicotine addiction for a lifetime.
Before human tests, further attempts are needed, which can take a few more years, but Professor Ronald Crystal from Weill Cornell Medical College in New York said the initial results are good.
"We are very hopeful that this type of vaccination strategy can once help millions of smokers who have tried to stop while trying all the methods available on the market, but have seen that their nicotine addiction is stronger than these approaches," said Cornell.
The new vaccine contains a harmless virus that has been modified to contain the genetic information for the production of nicotine antibodies.
The virus selectively infects the liver cells, which then produce a constant stream of antibodies.
The antibodies hunt the nicotine molecules in their blood and neutralize them before they reach the brain, which means that a smoker does not experience a nicotine high.
In experiments, vaccinated mice that were administered nicotine maintained their normal level of activity.
However, mice without vaccination had taken a "time out", the researchers explained, a sign that the nicotine had reached their brains.
The experiments are described in the journal Science Translational Medicine.
Earlier tobacco vaccines failed because they contained antibodies.
The vaccinations had to be given so often to maintain the antibody level that they were expensive and impractical.
However, the cost of the new vaccine is probably significantly lower, because it turns liver cells into antibody factories.
As Professor Crystal said, a future vaccine for people, if it was quite safe, could be given to children before they were tempted to try a cigarette, thus preventing nicotine addiction.
More likely, smokers would use it to stop.
"They know that when they start smoking again, they no longer feel pleasure because of the nicotine vaccine, and that helps them to put the habit of putting on," he explains.
British scientists said the results were interesting, but at the same time warned that further research was needed.
