Cry of despair of an Obama voter
I have elected President Obama twice in the hope that change is possible
He says Obama has made commendable efforts that have been thwarted by the Republican blockade tactics
The blockade policy does not excuse the website problems of Obamacare, the drone attacks
Obama's memoirs about the 2008 election campaign are a sad reminder of what would have been possible
Nathaniel P. Morris is a second-year student at Harvard Medical School.
I am currently reading a terribly sad book.
It is a book that I believed would be cheerful during the gloomy second year of my medical studies and give me hope again.
It's called "The Audacity to Win" and describes the memory of Barack Obama's presidential election in 2008.
When I finished with my patient desks in the evening and go to bed, the book leads me back to a time when politics inspired millions and a speech could take my breath away.
The election became a landslide victory and newscaster stopped to show the historical significance of this hour.
My classmates cried with joy and my parents gathered all the newspapers they could find.
A young team of visionaries was on their way to the White House and the nation was ready for change.
When Obama moved to office in 2008, he had approvals of 82%.
And then I close the book.
Switching back to the present is an evil awakening, as if you were torn out of a dream.
It is difficult to remember these optimistic times – they seem to be a vague memory, a sad admonition of missed opportunities.
In the years since I voted for the first time, something has actually changed.
But it's just nothing I could have imagined.
I recognize the great and varied things that Obama has achieved, from the passage of the Affordable Care Act for Health Insurance to the military withdrawal from Iraq, the end of forced concealment of homosexuality in the army and the killing of Osama bin Laden.
I too believe that the party-political blockade tactic has tipped too many efforts to bring our nation forward: immigration reform, a public option for health insurance and the closing of Guantanamo Bay, to name just a few.
But after defending the Obama administration towards colleagues and acquaintances countless times, I have ended up with my attempts at explanations.
I have reached a point of political despair.
The republican blocking policy cannot explain why one allows the listening of foreign heads of state or the killing of innocent children by drones overseas.
It cannot explain why the National Security Agency collects data about Americans' private lives and why whistleblowers are punished who disclose state misconduct.
It cannot explain why Anwar al-Awlaki, an American citizen, was murdered without proceedings, nor is there anyway the public financing and expenditure limits during the presidential elections.
It does not justify the results of a report, which states that the White House's efforts to encape the media are the "most aggressive since the Nixon government".
And recently, it cannot excuse the inability to design a simple website in the more than three years since the passing of the Affordable Care Act.
I don't know if that's what I should have expected.
Whether I should have understood at 18 that the work of the government could contradict the political campaigns it precedes.
Obviously, the office of parliament is not a predictable course, as an opposition party and accidental events such as the Newtown massacre shape the public debate.
But if I look at the above examples, they seem to be largely elected by the government itself.
And that bothers me the most.
I voted Obama again in 2012, not because I was enthusiastic about his candidacy.
Mitt Romney represented a confusing and unbaked alternative, he did not seem to be able to determine his direction and positions.
I had the impression that a second term for Obama, free from pressure from future elections, would fulfill the hope we had heard from for so long.
But with the fall of Obama’s approval ratings to below 45% this week, the return to 2008 has become all the more harsher through this book.
It awakens in me the longing for the many promises that have vanished into thin air.
This week I read a section in the book describing how Obama had to suffer a serious loss against Clinton in the Pennsylvania primary.
In a meeting with the election workers after the decision, he told his employees that they had to come back on track and follow the purpose of their cause.
"I want us to rediscover our spell," he said.
We need to remember who we are.
It is five years later, Mr. President, and I could not agree with you more.
The views expressed in this commentary are solely those of Nathaniel Morris.
